{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516315"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:41:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:41:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12596"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12596"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.86,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53081"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5089"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38496"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14315"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42786"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department after being found unresponsive at home by his roommate. According to the roommate, the patient first mentioned feeling unwell several hours earlier with some nausea, fatigue and confusion. He has a significant history of poorly controlled asthma on several inhalers, a previous appendicectomy, and a traumatic spinal injury for which he is on prescription long-acting analgesia. On examination he is pale and diaphoretic. His blood pressure is 95/68 mmHg, pulse 76/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 6/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 88% on room air. His GCS is E1V1M4.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nebulised Salbutamol","IV Flumazenil","IV Naloxone","Activated charcoal","IV N-acetylcysteine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with a decreased level of consciousness which is most likely due to opioid overdose. This is supported by his presentation with sedation, respiratory depression, and a known history of taking prescription pain medications. \u003Cstrong\u003ENaloxone \u003C/strong\u003Eis the drug of choice for the emergency treatment of any suspected opioid overdose. It is an opioid antagonist that rapidly reverses the effects of opioids and restores normal respiration. Naloxone can be administered intravenously, intramuscularly, or intranasally. The dose and route of administration depend on the severity of the overdose and the patient\u0027s response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised Salbutamol \u003C/strong\u003Eis used in the treatment of asthma exacerbations. Whilst this patient does have a history of poorly controlled asthma and has presented with hypoxia, his other symptoms (primarily respiratory depression and sedation) do not make sense in this context as the acute asthma patient would be expected to have an elevated respiratory rate. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlumazenil \u003C/strong\u003Eis a benzodiazepine antagonist that can reverse the effects of benzodiazepine overdose. However, it is not effective in the management of opioid overdose. Flumazenil should not be used in patients who have co-ingested benzodiazepines and opioids, as it can precipitate benzodiazepine withdrawal and worsen respiratory depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E is a decontamination agent commonly used in overdoses to inhibit absorption of ingested drugs. Whilst it is an important consideration in any patients where an overdose is suspected, this patients\u0027 time of ingestion is unknown and his symptoms started several hours ago, so he is likely outside of the window for administration (ideally within 1hr). In this case, even if he was within the ideal window, the administration of activated charcoal would only be appropriate once he had a secured airway and a nasogastric tube in situ. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-acetylcysteine \u003C/strong\u003Eis the treatment given for paracetamol overdose. Whilst this patient may be taking paracetamol as part of his analgesic regimen, an overdose of this drug would not explain his signs and symptoms and is therefore not the appropriate treatment. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Naloxone is the drug of choice for the emergency treatment of any suspected opioid overdose."],"references":["Schiller EY, Goyal A, Mechanic OJ. Opioid Overdose. 2022 Sep 19. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262202."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12596"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-16T17:30:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-16T17:31:11+09:30"},"rela